🐍 Python — Suggested Questions
Level 1: Basics (syntax, control flow)

Check if a number is prime / palindrome / Armstrong number
Reverse a string / number without built-in reverse
FizzBuzz
Find factorial (iterative + recursive)
Count vowels/consonants in a string

Level 2: Data structures

Find duplicates in a list
Find the second largest element in a list
Remove duplicates from a list without using set()
Implement a stack and queue using lists
Anagram checker
Word frequency counter using dictionaries
Matrix transpose / matrix multiplication

Level 3: Algorithms

Binary search (iterative + recursive)
Bubble sort, selection sort, merge sort (implement manually, not sorted())
Linear search vs binary search comparison
Fibonacci (recursive, iterative, memoized)
Two-sum problem
Sliding window: max sum subarray of size k

Level 4: OOP + File handling (since you're security-focused, this connects well)

Class-based implementation of a simple bank account / inventory system
Read/write to a file, basic file parser
Exception handling: custom exceptions
A simple Caesar cipher / XOR cipher implementation (ties into your crypto projects!)
Basic hash function implementation

Level 5: Security-flavored (since it's your specialization — this is your differentiator)

Simple password strength checker
Basic port scanner using socket
Log file parser to detect suspicious login attempts
URL/domain validator using regex
A basic keylogger detector or file integrity checker (hash comparison)


🇨 C — Suggested Questions
Level 1: Basics

Prime number check, Armstrong number, palindrome
Swap two numbers (with and without a third variable)
Reverse a string/array without built-in functions
Pattern printing (triangles, pyramids — shows control-flow comfort)

Level 2: Arrays & Strings

Find max/min in array
Bubble sort, selection sort, insertion sort (manual implementation — very commonly asked)
String length, string reverse, string comparison (without strlen, strrev, strcmp)
Matrix addition/multiplication
Find duplicates in an array

Level 3: Pointers & Memory (this is where C interviews really test you)

Pointer arithmetic examples
Dynamic memory allocation (malloc, calloc, free) — e.g. dynamic array
Swap using pointers
Function pointers example
Simple linked list: insert, delete, traverse, reverse

Level 4: Data Structures

Stack implementation using array
Queue implementation using array
Singly linked list operations
Binary search implementation
Recursion: factorial, Fibonacci, GCD (Euclidean algorithm)

Level 5: Security-flavored / systems-level (great differentiator for SOC-analyst goals)

Simple XOR encryption/decryption program
Basic Caesar cipher in C
Simple checksum / hash implementation
Bitwise operations demo (AND, OR, XOR, shifts) — relevant to security & networking
A simple command-line password validator


How to structure this in your repos
For each question, include:

Problem statement (as a comment or separate .md)
Your solution code
A one-line note on time/space complexity (shows you think about efficiency, not just correctness)

This way an interviewer skimming your repo folder names instantly sees: fundamentals → data structures → pointers/OOP → security applications — a clear signal of both your coding level and your specialization.
